**Degree of freedom** (d.f.)
- property calculated from the sample data
- It is an "input" in many [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/statistical tests|statistical tests]] : **commonly used in** $\chi^2$-test, [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/t-test|t-test]] (t-distribution), [[___INBOX___/__à trier/F-test|F-test]] (F-distribution), ...
	- in **t-test** : it affects the shape of the t-distribution
	- same in [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/Chi-squared test of independence|Chi-squared test of independence]]
- It's a more general property than the "number of categories" (eg. in chi-squared test for goodness of fit)
- It represents the maximum number of logically **independent values** that are free to vary/move without violating **constraints** (eg. the estimation of the mean)
	- eg. if you know the mean for a sample of 10 values there are 9 degree of freedom => once you know 9 values, ==the 10th can be calculated, and is not free to vary==
	- number of information that went into calculating the estimate
- a general formula is "number of observations **minus** number of relations"
	- eg. for a sample mean (average) : $d.f. = n-1$
- **Not very important in** [[___INBOX___/__à trier/Data Science|data science]], when we have lots of data (n or n-1 doesn't make much difference)
- Useful in regression (including [[Topics/Machine Learning/Models/Logistic regression|Logistic regression]]), to prevent "multicollinearity error" => ?
